1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg4 {Taking advantage of the 
fact that h3 has not been played yet. But In the majority of these positions, 
White won the majority of his games.} 6. Nbd2 {Rather than playing h3, we play 
Nbd2 to meet Bxf3 with Nxf3 rather than with Qxf3, another idea of Nbd2 is to 
play Nc4 followed by Ne3.} Bg7 {developing the bishop.} 7. h3 {Kicking the 
bishop. Black will be inclined to capture the knight, if black retreats, Bg4 
would seem like a wasted move, and the light squared bishop will forever be 
dominated and controlled.} Bxf3 8. Nxf3 Nf6 $14 {White already has a slight edge 
in this position. black's structure is slightly worse.} 9. O-O Nd7 {Black delays 
castling to prevent the bishop on c1 from going to e3. This also defends c5.} 
10. Be3 $1 {Bxb2 runs into Rb1, and that snatches off the b7 pawn, leaving black 
no possibilities on the queenside and a very weakened pawn structure on the 
c-file.} O-O 11. c3 e5 *

[Event "Sicilian Rossolimo for white"]
[Site "Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...bxc6 6...Nf6 8...Nb6"]
