1. e4 c5 {We enter the Sicilian. Many players as white just do not like the 
theory to this opening because there are so many things to do. I am going to try 
to explain this as simply as possible so that you (the player) can enjoy playing 
open sicilians without going into anti-sicilians. (Many of which can and will be 
refuted. Such as the Grand prix attack) .} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {This is one of the main 
moves in the sicilian. Excluding d6, e6 and even g6 at some states. But Nc6 is 
the second most popular move, and you can see this in many tournaments.} 3. Bb5 
{This is the Rossolimo Variation. A very annoying reply from white. No matter 
what black is going to do next turn, white is going to snatch off that knight 
with his light squared bishop. This seems very counter-intuitive but giving away 
the bishop for weak pawns on black's queenside is worthwhile. White gets his 
bishop out of his pawn chain, and prepares to go into a Ruy-lopez type structure 
for white. White may look for an attack on the kingside in these positions.} g6 
{The main move. Hoping to fianchetto the bishop on g7 to overlook the long 
diagonal. Other moves are e6, d6, and Nf6.} 4. Bxc6 {Now it depends how black 
re-captures here. Capturing with the b-pawn can give his rook some play down the 
b-file. But limits his development of the light squared bishop. Capturing with 
the d-pawn brings a pawn away from the center but black can develop his bishop 
with less limitations} bxc6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Nf6 {The other alternative is Nf6. 
Which is a more simpler way to play the position.} 7. e5 Nd5 8. c4 Nc7 {Not 
blocking the b-file with Nb6. This gives black more flexible options} 9. d4 {d4 
is appropriate now.} cxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Qh4 $5 {A very sneaky move, preparing 
Bh6. Followed by Bxg7 and then Ng5. a very deadly plan which can end poorly for 
black.} f6 {Attempting to stop Ng5 and also contest the center.} 12. Nc3 
{Developing another piece. With the idea of going to e4.} Ne6 {The knight on c7 
was a poor piece. On e6 it can defend the kingside and become more active.} 13. 
Ne4 fxe5 {Completely ignore this pawn. White gets immense compensation} 14. Nfg5 
Nxg5 15. Bxg5 {Now e7 is hanging.} Qb6 16. Rad1 {Taking on e7 is a bad idea 
because of Rf4. So simply playing Rad1 and offering b2 is a good way to play. 
Looking for activity down the center and the kingside. Black can easily get in 
trouble in these positions. The light squared bishop is severely restricted.} 
Qxb2 17. g3 d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Rxd5 Bf5 20. Rd2 Qb7 21. Bxe7 Rf7 22. Ba3 
{Zhigalko S 2664 VS Guseinov G 2616 1-0 White has a more active position and won 
the game eventually.} *

