moves in the sicilian. Excluding d6, e6 and even g6 at some states. But Nc6 is 
the second most popular move, and you can see this in many tournaments.} 3. Bb5 
{This is the Rossolimo Variation. A very annoying reply from white. No matter 
what black is going to do next turn, white is going to snatch off that knight 
with his light squared bishop. This seems very counter-intuitive but giving away 
the bishop for weak pawns on black's queenside is worthwhile. White gets his 
bishop out of his pawn chain, and prepares to go into a Ruy-lopez type structure 
for white. White may look for an attack on the kingside in these positions.} g6 
{The main move. Hoping to fianchetto the bishop on g7 to overlook the long 
diagonal. Other moves are e6, d6, and Nf6.} 4. Bxc6 {Now it depends how black 
re-captures here. Capturing with the b-pawn can give his rook some play down the 
b-file. But limits his development of the light squared bishop. Capturing with 
the d-pawn brings a pawn away from the center but black can develop his bishop 
with less limitations} bxc6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Nh6 {The idea behind this move is 
to play f6 or f5 and re-route the knight to f7. Where it will aim for e5 or d6 
in some cases.} 7. c3 {Blunting the bishop on g7. Also prepares d4.} O-O 8. h3 
$5 {This is a recent idea that has been played by Masters from Anand, Svidler 
and Caruana. It blocks the knight from coming to g4 in some cases. Often you see 
black play Ng4 after white plays Be3. h3 however, prevents that idea completely. 
It also holds off on d4 for a moment, white is in absolutely no rush. h3 is also 
useful in preventing Bg4 from black.} f5 {Breaking on the kingside. This allows 
a re-route square for the knight on h6. But it also gains some space on the 
kingside. The downsides is that the black king becomes slightly exposed, and f5 
is no longer an available square for the knight. This also allows white to play 
e5!} 9. e5 Nf7 10. d3 {d4 might look very tempting, but it has bad results in 
practice for white. Im sure it is because white's pawns become over extended. 
The 2 main moves for black after d3 is Ba6 to develop the bishop, or Rb8 to 
attack b2.} Ba6 11. c4 {Blunting the bishop on a6. White has to keep the light 
squared bishop completely inactive for white to prove that giving away the light 
squared bishop early in the game was worthwhile.} d6 {Trying to breakup the e5 
pawn to unleash the bishop on g7.} 12. e6 Ne5 13. Nc3 {Developing another piece. 
White's main plan is to keep the a6 bishop inactive, and create play down the 
center.} Rb8 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Na4 {Threatning Nxc5.} Bd4 16. Bh6 *

