[SourceTitle "02 Rossolimo 3..e6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "sicilian-rossolimo-for-white/course/5314, variation/206787"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {This has the idea of bringing the knight into e7 
to support the knight on c6. This is too slow however, and white can take the 
bishop immediately.} 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. b3 $5 {An interesting idea that was played 
by many players before such as Carlsen and Caruana. The idea is to Fianchetto 
the bishop on b2 and extert pressure down the center that way. This may come as 
a surprise to players who only study main line theory.} f6 {Blunting the bishop 
on b2 if it ever goes there, and also preventing e5. A decent move.} 6. O-O {So 
why not Bb2 here? Well, white has to make sure that when knight h6 is played, he 
has a chance to play d4! Which allows the bishop on c1 to take the knight on 
h6.} Nh6 {The knight has to develop one way or another. An idea here is to 
reroute it through f7.} 7. d4 $1 Nf7 {7. d4 cxd4 is bad because if 7. d4 cxd4 8. 
Bxh6! gxh6 9. Qxd4 and black is worse simply because of all his weakened pawns. 
So the knight has to be moved.} 8. Ba3 $1 {Targetting c5.} cxd4 9. Bxf8 Kxf8 
{Black loses his right to castle.} 10. Qxd4 e5 11. Qd2 d5 12. Nc3 {White stands 
fine here.} *

