1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {This has the idea of bringing the knight into e7 
to support the knight on c6. This is too slow however, and white can take the 
bishop immediately.} 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. b3 $5 {An interesting idea that was played 
by many players before such as Carlsen and Caruana. The idea is to Fianchetto 
the bishop on b2 and extert pressure down the center that way. This may come as 
a surprise to players who only study main line theory.} d5 {The most testing 
move in this variation. Breaking in the center and gaining space with d5. Make 
sure to avoid taking black's d-pawn because then black will fix his structure. 
c6 will no longer be a weakness.} 6. e5 Ba6 {Attempting to develop the bishop to 
a decent diagonal.} 7. d3 {Blunting the bishop. As it was preventing us from 
castling.} c4 {This is the usual idea behind Ba6.} 8. dxc4 dxc4 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 
10. Ba3 Ne7 {Black would not want to take our bishop, because if he takes, we 
develop the knight and attack c4. And if cxb3 after that, we play axb3 and open 
up our rooks.} *

