the bishop on b2 and extert pressure down the center that way. This may come as 
a surprise to players who only study main line theory.} Ne7 {Bringing the knight 
to e7 to reroute to g6.} 6. Bb2 Ng6 7. h4 $1 {Taking advantage of the misplaced 
knight on g6.} h5 {This cannot be ignored. Black has to play h5 to avoid h5 from 
white.} 8. e5 {Gaining more space in the center.} c4 {An interesting pawn 
sacrifice to open up black's pieces.} 9. bxc4 Rb8 10. Bc3 {Rxb2 was a threat.} 
c5 11. d3 $14 {White is much better here.} Be7 12. Nbd2 f5 13. g3 $16 {defending 
h4.} *

