[Comment "sicilian-rossolimo-for-white/course/5314, variation/245144"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {A system that has been employed by black for a 
long time. Kasparov and Kramnik used to play this as black. The idea is to play 
Nge7-g6 or to push d5.} 4. Bxc6 {In the style of the Rossolimo. We are going to 
grab the knight and double the pawn structure before black can even bring his 
knight to e7 to support c6. Black now has a choice between dxc6 and bxc6. Both 
come with good and bad aspects.} dxc6 5. O-O g6 {Black should probably not do 
this, the combination of e6 and g6 only weaken his dark squares.} 6. d3 Bg7 {Now 
d6 is weak because the bishop is no longer on f8.} 7. e5 {clamps on d6, shuts 
out f6 and the bishop on g7.} Ne7 8. Nbd2 Qc7 {Bologan-Adamczewski 2011.} 9. Ne4 
{Now Nd6 is a massive threat.} O-O 10. Re1 {to defend e5.} Nd5 11. c4 Nb6 12. 
Bf4 $16 {White has very strong control over d6 and the dark squares. Black is 
lost because his pieces and his dark squares are difficult to defend well. c5 is 
also hanging.} *

