1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {A system that has been employed by black for a 
long time. Kasparov and Kramnik used to play this as black. The idea is to play 
Nge7-g6 or to push d5.} 4. Bxc6 {In the style of the Rossolimo. We are going to 
grab the knight and double the pawn structure before black can even bring his 
knight to e7 to support c6. Black now has a choice between dxc6 and bxc6. Both 
come with good and bad aspects.} bxc6 {Black opens the b-file and also helps 
black play d5 at some moment} 5. b3 $5 {This is not the most popular move, but 
the idea is very interesting for white. He wants to compensate for the lack of 
light squared bishop by placing his pawns on light squares to limit the bishop 
on c8. Especially since d7 and e6 are on the board. This has been played before 
by players like Anand, Carlsen, Shirov, Bok, Adams, and many more.} d5 {Simply 
grabbing the center. This does however weaken c5 indirectly.} 6. Nc3 $5 
{Developing a piece, this invites forward d4, though black should not play 
that-because it overextends his pawn structure-Causing weaknesses and problems. 
This looks strange, but the idea is to prepare Na4 and Ba3 to pressurize c5.} g5 
{Played between Adams and Gregoire in 2006. This hands white an edge, as g5 only 
weakens black's kingside.} 7. O-O {This was a slight improvement from what Adams 
played.} Bg7 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Re1 {Although it looks like we just gave the center 
to black because we lack any pawns in the center, black actually cant exploit 
this. if d4-then Na4 followed by Ba3 make c5 vulnerable.} h6 10. Ba3 Qa5 11. Na4 
$1 {Accepting the exchange sacrifice on a1 would not give black good results.} 
Bxa1 $2 12. Qxa1 f6 {To block out the rook.} 13. c4 {With the threat of cxd5.} 
dxc4 14. Qb2 {The threat is subtle. But it defends a3 and prepares Nxc5, which 
will win the c5 pawn and attack e6. White is completely dominating black.} Kf7 
15. Nxc5 Rb8 16. Nd4 $1 *

