1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {A system that has been employed by black for a 
long time. Kasparov and Kramnik used to play this as black. The idea is to play 
Nge7-g6 or to push d5.} 4. Bxc6 {In the style of the Rossolimo. We are going to 
grab the knight and double the pawn structure before black can even bring his 
knight to e7 to support c6. Black now has a choice between dxc6 and bxc6. Both 
come with good and bad aspects.} bxc6 {Black opens the b-file and also helps 
black play d5 at some moment} 5. b3 $5 {This is not the most popular move, but 
the idea is very interesting for white. He wants to compensate for the lack of 
light squared bishop by placing his pawns on light squares to limit the bishop 
on c8. Especially since d7 and e6 are on the board. This has been played before 
by players like Anand, Carlsen, Shirov, Bok, Adams, and many more.} Ne7 
{re-routing the knight to g6. White can easily oppose this with h4-h5.} 6. Bb2 
Ng6 7. h4 h5 {Prevents h5.} 8. e5 {Further limiting black. Taking away f6 and 
e5. As well as weakening d6.} c4 $5 {Interesting, but black does not equalize. 
Black wants to give up his c pawn to get rid of the weak structure.} 9. bxc4 Rb8 
10. Bc3 c5 11. d3 Be7 12. Nbd2 f5 {Black needs to take away e4 from white.} 13. 
g3 {Defending h4.} Bb7 14. Qe2 Qb6 15. Rg1 {The idea looks strange at first, but 
it unpins from the bishop on b7, and tries to re-rout the knight to h2 so that 
white can play f4 and close the kingside.} Qc6 16. a4 Ba8 17. Nh2 {with the idea 
to play f4.} Rh6 {The idea is to re-rout the poor knight on g6 to h8-f7 to cover 
g5. Since white's next plan is to play Ndf3-g5.} 18. f4 Nh8 19. Ndf3 Nf7 20. Kd2 
{Connecting the rooks, since the position is closed on the kingside, white will 
have to focus his play on the queenside. White should direct his g1 rook to b1.} 
Rh8 {McShane-Grischuk 2003} 21. Rgb1 Rxb1 22. Rxb1 {a4 is untouchable because of 
Rb8.} g6 {to bring the king to f8-g7.} 23. Rb8+ Bd8 24. Qe1 Kf8 25. Qb1 Kg7 {Ba5 
was threatened.} 26. Qb5 $16 *

