[Comment "sicilian-rossolimo-for-white/course/5314, variation/208013"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 {This position can also occur from a Najdorf 
variation. first with d6 and Bb5+ and then Nc6. Black tries to bring his bishop 
to d7 to capture the knight with the bishop, another idea is to open up the 
bishop immediately with a diagonal.} 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 {White gives up the bishop to 
give black a weakness on the c-file. It is vital to make sure that weakness 
prevails so white can have some play. Playing d4 in these positions is a bad 
idea because it lets go of black's weakness on c6. However, white can now play 
d3 without a poor piece on f1.} 5. O-O e5 {This is the main line besides Bg4.} 
6. c3 {preparing d4 at some stage.} Nf6 {Black in this position is always 
looking to play d5 at some point to fix his structure and repair the weaknesses 
he has with his pawn structure.} 7. Re1 Be7 {Is also a possible move. To quickly 
castle and get the king to safety.} 8. d4 {Breaking in the center. Although this 
seems counter-intuative to help black with his weakness, he will still have 
problems with his pawns. The c and d pawns will be suffering for most of the 
game. the a-pawn is also going to suffer because it is isolated. But white's 
pieces beging to develop quickly into the position.} cxd4 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Nxd4 
*

