1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 {This position can also occur from a Najdorf 
variation. first with d6 and Bb5+ and then Nc6. Black tries to bring his bishop 
to d7 to capture the knight with the bishop, another idea is to open up the 
bishop immediately with a diagonal.} 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 {White gives up the bishop to 
give black a weakness on the c-file. It is vital to make sure that weakness 
prevails so white can have some play. Playing d4 in these positions is a bad 
