give black a weakness on the c-file. It is vital to make sure that weakness 
prevails so white can have some play. Playing d4 in these positions is a bad 
idea because it lets go of black's weakness on c6. However, white can now play 
d3 without a poor piece on f1.} 5. O-O Bg4 {The main move in this variation. 
Black gets his light squared bishop out exploiting the fact that we gave our 
bishop up. This is not a big deal however.} 6. h3 Bh5 {Black preserves his 
bishop.} 7. e5 $1 {A key move to give white an edge in the position. The idea is 
to tear apart black's d6 pawn and truly expose the weakness on the c-file.} dxe5 
{Black capturing the pawn truly leaves the c-file weak. The pawns there are 
severely weakened. The a-pawn is also isolated.} 8. g4 {In return for the 
weakened structure, white slightly weakens his king.} e4 9. gxh5 exf3 10. Nc3 $1 
{Before rushing to recapture the pawn. We want to avoid Qd4. Which attacks the 
h5 pawn, protects f3, and defends c6.} Nf6 11. Qxf3 Rc8 {defending c6.} 12. d3 
{Opening up the bishop. In general, white needs to protect his kingside. But he 
does have plenty of targets on black's queenside.} e6 13. Re1 Be7 14. Bf4 Nd5 
15. Be5 O-O 16. Rad1 *

