[SourceTitle "04 Rossolimo 3...Nf6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "sicilian-rossolimo-for-white/course/5314, variation/208011"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {The 4th most popular move here.} 4. Bxc6 
{Although this is not the main line. White has pretty decent results here and 
for simplicity sake taking on c6 is going to be our main plan all the time for 
the first 4 moves.} dxc6 {This allows more free development for his light 
squared bishop.} 5. d3 {Protecting the e-pawn.} Bg4 {Black gets out his light 
sqauared bishop into the game. Very simple development.} 6. h3 Bh5 7. Nc3 {White 
develops a piece to c3. There is no need for d4 in the meantime because once 
again black has these weaknesses on the c-file. It is not appropriate at the 
moment.} Nd7 $5 {An interesting idea. The nuance behind this is to avoid a Ne5 
idea from white. If white had another move, he would play g4, and after Bg6 Ne5! 
to prepare f4. And black has to spend an extra tempo playing Nd7 to exchange 
that knight off. This is why Nf6 is the 4th most popular move, because the 
knight on f6 is often misplaced in these positions.} 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bf4 {White 
enjoys a good position out of the opening.} e6 10. Qd2 {Prepping longside 
castle.} Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. h4 h5 13. Rdg1 $1 {Piling on the kingside.} *

